/F2 15 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 732.0 Tm (Two Sleeps and a Shimmer: Quiet and Active Sleep States in the Common Octopus) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 718.0 Tm () Tj
/F1 9 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 704.0 Tm (Sofia Marchenko and Daniel Ofori) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 690.0 Tm (Journal of Cephalopod Neuroscience, Vol. 8, No. 3 \(2021\) - JID-012) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 676.0 Tm () Tj
/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 658.0 Tm (Abstract) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 644.0 Tm (Sleep with distinct quiet and active phases was long thought confined to vertebrates.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 630.0 Tm (Filming undisturbed common octopuses across multiple nights, we document a recurring) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 616.0 Tm (transition from a pale, still quiet state into brief bouts of rapid skin-pattern change, eye) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 602.0 Tm (movement, and muscular twitching that we term active sleep. The cycle's timing and the) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 588.0 Tm (difficulty of rousing the animal during it parallel features of vertebrate sleep, suggesting) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 574.0 Tm (a convergent solution in a nervous system organised on entirely different lines.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 560.0 Tm () Tj
/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 542.0 Tm (Introduction) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 528.0 Tm (Sleep that alternates between quiet and active phases, the latter marked in mammals by rapid) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 514.0 Tm (eye movement and vivid dreaming, has been one of the more reliable dividing lines between) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 500.0 Tm (vertebrate and invertebrate nervous systems. The octopus, with its large brain built on a) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 486.0 Tm (wholly different plan, is an ideal place to test whether that line really holds.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 472.0 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 56 458.0 Tm (We set out to characterise the rest behaviour of the common octopus in detail, asking) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 444.0 Tm (whether its quiescent periods are uniform or whether they contain structure resembling the) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 430.0 Tm (alternating states seen in vertebrates.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 416.0 Tm () Tj
/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 398.0 Tm (Observation Protocol) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 384.0 Tm (Individual octopuses were housed in quiet tanks and filmed continuously under low light) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 370.0 Tm (across several nights, after a long acclimation period to ensure the behaviour was) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 356.0 Tm (undisturbed. We scored skin colour and texture, eye movement, arm posture, and breathing) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 342.0 Tm (rate.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 328.0 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 56 314.0 Tm (To test depth of rest, we presented mild, standardised stimuli at intervals and recorded how) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 300.0 Tm (readily the animal responded. A rest state from which the animal is hard to rouse behaves) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 286.0 Tm (like sleep rather than mere stillness, an important criterion for the claims that follow.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 272.0 Tm () Tj
/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 254.0 Tm (The Active State) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 240.0 Tm (For most of its rest the octopus lay pale, still, and evenly breathing, a condition we call) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 226.0 Tm (quiet sleep. Punctuating this, roughly once an hour, came short bouts of dramatic change:) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 212.0 Tm (the skin flickered through rapid patterns, the eyes moved, the arms twitched, and breathing) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 198.0 Tm (grew irregular. These bouts lasted under a minute before the animal sank back into the quiet) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 184.0 Tm (state.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 170.0 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 56 156.0 Tm (During these active bouts the octopuses were markedly harder to rouse than during quiet) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 142.0 Tm (rest, ruling out the possibility that the skin display was simply a response to some) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 128.0 Tm (external disturbance. The animal was, by our criteria, more deeply asleep precisely when it) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 114.0 Tm (appeared most active.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 100.0 Tm () Tj
/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 82.0 Tm (Convergence, Not Inheritance) Tj
