/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 736.0 Tm (The parallel with vertebrate active sleep is striking, but we are cautious about its) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 722.0 Tm (meaning. The last common ancestor of octopuses and vertebrates was a simple creature that) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 708.0 Tm (almost certainly had nothing resembling this two-state sleep. Any similarity is therefore) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 694.0 Tm (convergent: two very different brains arriving independently at a similar organisation of) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 680.0 Tm (rest.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 666.0 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 56 652.0 Tm (What problem does the active state solve, that two lineages should both evolve it? We do not) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 638.0 Tm (claim to know. The convergence does suggest, however, that alternating sleep states answer) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 624.0 Tm (some general need of complex nervous systems rather than being a quirk of vertebrate) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 610.0 Tm (history, and that the octopus is a powerful test case for whatever that need turns out to) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 596.0 Tm (be.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 582.0 Tm () Tj
/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 564.0 Tm (Conclusion) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 550.0 Tm (The common octopus exhibits a recurring active sleep state, complete with skin-pattern) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 536.0 Tm (flickering, eye movement, and reduced rousability, embedded within longer periods of quiet) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 522.0 Tm (sleep. Arising in a nervous system unrelated to ours, this two-state architecture points to) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 508.0 Tm (convergent evolution and marks the octopus as a key organism for understanding why complex) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 494.0 Tm (brains sleep the way they do.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 480.0 Tm () Tj
